        <p>Dating as a single dad is different. You're not just deciding whether you like someone — you're thinking about your kids, your schedule, your custody arrangement, your own emotional state, and whether this person fits into a life that's already full. That's a lot of variables. Here's a framework that helps.</p>

        <h2>When to start</h2>
        <p>There's no universal answer. Some dads date while still processing the divorce; some wait a year or more. A few things worth asking yourself honestly:</p>
        <ul>
          <li>Are you dating because you want connection, or because you want distraction?</li>
          <li>Can you talk about your ex without anger taking over?</li>
          <li>Do you have enough emotional bandwidth for another person on top of everything else?</li>
        </ul>
        <p>You don't have to be "fully healed" — that's not a real destination. But going in with self-awareness is better for you and fairer to the people you meet.</p>

        <h2>Managing the time reality</h2>
        <p>Dating requires time you probably don't have a lot of. A few things that help:</p>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Date during your off-custody time</strong> when possible. This keeps your kids' time protected and removes the childcare logistics entirely.</li>
          <li><strong>Be upfront early</strong> that your schedule is constrained. Someone who can't handle that isn't the right fit anyway — and finding out early saves both of you time.</li>
          <li><strong>Start with lower-commitment formats</strong> — coffee, lunch, a walk. Less pressure, shorter time blocks, easier to fit in without a full evening babysitter.</li>
        </ul>

        <h2>What to tell your kids (and when)</h2>
        <p>Most child psychologists suggest keeping early dating separate from your kids until the relationship is established. A few dates in, you don't know yet if this person is going anywhere. Introducing them too early creates unnecessary confusion and attachment.</p>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Before you introduce anyone:</strong> you should have been dating for at least a few months, have a sense the relationship has real potential, and feel genuinely comfortable with how this person would interact with your children.</li>
          <li><strong>The first introduction</strong> should be low-key — a casual meeting, not a big event. Give your kids room to form their own impression without pressure.</li>
          <li><strong>Age matters.</strong> Younger kids may bond quickly and be confused by a breakup. Older kids may have strong feelings about you dating at all. Both deserve honest, age-appropriate conversations.</li>
          <li><strong>Never ask your kids to keep your dating a secret from their other parent.</strong> It puts them in a loyalty conflict they shouldn't be in.</li>
        </ul>

        <h2>What to look for (that you might not have thought about before)</h2>
        <p>Your priorities in a partner may look different now than they did before kids. Things that matter more:</p>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>How they feel about kids — specifically, your kids.</strong> Not in theory, but in practice. Do they ask about them? Show genuine interest? Or do your kids feel like a complication to work around?</li>
          <li><strong>Flexibility and low drama.</strong> Your life requires adaptability. Someone who gets upset when plans change isn't going to work well in your reality.</li>
          <li><strong>Their own family situation.</strong> Do they have kids? How do they co-parent? Those dynamics will eventually intersect with yours.</li>
          <li><strong>Your co-parenting relationship.</strong> Someone who inflames conflict with your ex — even if your ex is difficult — creates a problem you'll live with for a long time.</li>
        </ul>

        <div class="callout">
          <p><strong>You're allowed to have standards.</strong> Single fatherhood can make you feel like you should be grateful for anyone willing to date a man with kids. That's backwards. Your situation asks more of a partner — and that means you should be more thoughtful about who you choose, not less.</p>
        </div>

